eritage. Building on the work of theorists ranging from Edward Said to Édouard Glissant, this book expands our understanding of how national and racial imaginaries develop, why they persist, and how they might be subverted. As it confronts Hispaniola’s dark legacies of slavery and colonial oppression, The Dominican Racial Imaginary also delivers an inspiring message on how multicultural communities might cooperate to disrupt the enduring power of white supremacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAnti-racismxHistoryxDominican Republic. 0aAnti-racismzDominican RepublicxHistory. 0aBlack peoplezDominican RepublicxHistory. 0aBlacksxHistoryxDominican Republic. 0aBlackszDominican RepublicxHistory. 0aCreolesxHistoryxDominican Republic. 0aCreoleszDominican RepublicxHistory. 0aCultural pluralismxHistoryxDominican Republic. 0aCultural pluralismzDominican RepublicxHistory. 0aEthnicityxHistoryxDominican Republic. 0aEthnicityzDominican RepublicxHistory. 0aNationalismxHistoryxDominican Republic. 0aNationalismzDominican RepublicxHistory. 0aRacismxHistoryxDominican Republic. 0aRacismzDominican RepublicxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  adominican, dominican republic, african, ancestry, african american, latin american, identity, racial identity, haiti, haitian, hispaniola, dominican haitian, racial, race, racial imaginary.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066614440uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081358450840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813584508423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813584508/original  a978-3-11-066614-4  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  a